<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900410-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>900410-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Taiwan Oil Company   Set to Buy Huffington</HL><DATE>04/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17</SO><CO>   FREST</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)PETROLEUM (PET)OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)</IN><LP>   HOUSTON -- A longtime Texas oil company, Huffington Corp.,agreed to be acquired by Taiwan's national oil company.   Terms weren't disclosed, but an industry official familiarwith Huffington's assets valued them at $700 million to $900million. Huffington's primary asset is a 20% interest in anIndonesian joint venture, which supplies natural gas to oneof the world's largest liquefied-natural-gas facilities.</LP><TEXT>   Chinese Petroleum Corp., the Taiwan oil company, said itrecently began receiving liquified-natural gas, or LNG, fromthe facility. The company said that under a sales accord withIndonesia's state oil company, Pertamina, it imports 1.5million tons a year of LNG from that country.   Roy M. Huffington, founder of Huffington about 30 yearsago, said in a statement that &quot;this acquisition represents avery promising strategic opportunity&quot; for Chinese Petroleum.   It is believed that a group from Japan, another a bigimporter of LNG, was interested in acquiring Huffington. Thecompany put itself up for sale in November.   In addition to the energy assets, Huffington owns about 11blocks in downtown Houston and 419 acres of undevelopedHouston real estate. Huffington sold its domestic oil and gasreserves in August 1988 to France's Elf Aquitaine.</TEXT></DOC>